  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- Patriot Act (Title III specifically addresses money laundering)\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Establish reporting thresholds for cash transactions\n- Criminalize money laundering activities\n- Impose penalties and potential asset forfeiture\n- Mandate customer identification and record-keeping\n\n3. Enforcement Agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service (IRS)\n- Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)\n\n4. State Level:\nMany states also have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws\n\n5. International Cooperation:\nThe U.S. works with international organizations like FATF (Financial Action Task Force) to combat global money laundering\n\nThese statutes aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income and to track and prosecute financial crimes.",
